[2] South America (Argentina): alert
Date: Fri 20 Jul 2018 1:07pm
Source: The Bubble [edited]
http://www.thebubble.com/measles-outbreak-argentina/

Today [Fri 20 Jul 2018], the Argentine Ministry of Health released an epidemiological alert in which they confirmed that there had been at least 2 reported cases of measles in babies in Argentina. The report went on to urge people to take a number of "control measures" to protect themselves and their children from the outbreak.

The official statement released by the Ministry of Health stated: "Yesterday [Thu 19 Jul 2018], we confirmed 2 cases of measles in Buenos Aires. In view of this situation and the overall epidemiological context, the Ministry of Health of the Nation urges local health teams to verify the vaccination status of the population, sensitize the epidemiological surveillance of the febrile exanthematic disease, and respond quickly and adequately to identify any possible cases".

The reported cases both involved babies who had not been vaccinated against measles yet because of their young age. The 1st was a 5-month-old boy from the City of Buenos Aires, who began showing symptoms on [Thu 12 Jul 2018]. The 2nd was a 6-month old girl from the Province of Buenos Aires, diagnosed the next day [Fri 13 Jul 2018].

"Both cases presented similar symptoms (fever, rash, cough, and conjunctivitis)," stated Argentina's Minister of Health, Adolfo Rubinstein. "...both cases were confirmed by IgM serology and viral genome detection by PCR in a urine and respiratory sample."
In response to the outbreak, Rubinstein issued an order for the Ministry of Health to control the area in which the measles cases occurred, and conduct a full investigation to determine the source of the infection.

A few weeks ago, there were reported cases of measles in Russia, and warnings were issued to those traveling to the country for the 2018 World Cup. One hypothesis put forward by speculators is that one of the babies could have come into contact with someone who brought back the disease from abroad.

Meanwhile, in an interview with Clarin, Carla Vizzotti, President of the Argentine Society of Vaccinology and Epidemiology (SAVE), explained: "They are 2 babies who did not travel, who were not vaccinated because they were not old enough to be vaccinated. We are investigating whether they had contact with someone who traveled. The outbreak was confirmed yesterday [Thu 19 Jul 2018] and we are now investigating the places where they went, the possible places where they came in contact with the disease."

While the case of the 5-month-old in the city of Buenos Aires is still a mystery, in the case of the 6-month-old in the province, preliminary investigations have concluded that she caught the disease after coming into contact with a 21-year-old unvaccinated man who had contracted measles during a trip to Thailand

[Byline: Allie Pitchon]

