[3] Amazonas
Date: Wed 18 Jul 2018
Source: Efecto Cocuyo [in Spanish, machine trans., edited]
http://efectococuyo.com/salud/autoridades-de-amazonas-confirman-7-casos-de-sarampion-en-comunidades-yanomami/


Measles continues to spread to indigenous communities. The regional director of health of Amazonas, Jesus Bernabe Yuriyuri, confirmed that there are 7 cases of the disease in indigenous people of the Yanomami ethnic group in the Alto Orinoco municipality. The official indicated that the records correspond to the samples taken in the communities of Oroshi and Irotha since last April [2018].

However, in declarations offered this [Mon 16 Jul 2018], Yuriyuri did not refer to the denunciations of deaths that have been made by NGOs in charge of protecting indigenous rights.

The director reported that "in the next few hours" air support is expected to make the transfer to the communities and confirm the reports of deaths from the virus.

The Kape Kape Civil Association reported that it has received warnings about a possible outbreak in the community Irotatheri, 19 kilometers [11.8 miles approx.] from the border with Brazil , and on deaths of "a considerable number" of people who had symptoms of measles , such as high fever, difficulty Respiratory and convulsions.

Brazilian authorities from the border state of Roraima register 412 cases of measles in the state, of which only 200 have been confirmed. By [Wed May 30 2018], he indicates, 57 were of Venezuelan origin and 34 came from indigenous communities.

The Yanomami are not the only ethnic group that has been affected by the re-emergence of measles in the national territory. In April of this year [2018] the Kape Kape civil association denounced the death of at least 12 children of the Warao community in the Delta Amacurostate.

Subsequently, the Pan American Health Organization (PAHO) confirmed in a bulletin the death of 33 indigenous people of the Warao ethnic group and the import of cases to Brazil, Colombia, Peru and Ecuador.

PAHO reported in a report dated June 2018 that the epidemic of measles has spread to 21 states of Venezuela and the District Capital. At that time, it registered 2285 confirmed cases, of which more than half occurred so far in 2018.

It also indicates that Brazil registers an outbreak of measles in progress, with a total of 995 reported cases. Up to 611 of them are concentrated in the state of Amazonas and another 384 in the state of Roraima , the 2 entities closest to the border with Venezuela.

In June of this year [2018] the regional body reported that 114 cases had been confirmed to date and that the disease left 2 deaths in the neighboring country.

Among the reasons for the spread of the virus, PAHO lists the low vaccination coverage, the lack of an adequate surveillance system, the delay in the application of measures to control the disease, the poor ability to isolate patients and an intense movement at borders with neighboring countries during the period of incubation or transmission of the virus.

[Byline: Julett Pineda Sleinan]

